Raw dev notes -- "Excel, My Old Foe: Planning Agent Progress & Roadmaps"

**Project Background:**
The RH-Planner-Agent project is all about empowering our human planners to make smarter, faster inventory decisions. It's an agent designed to automate or optimize parts of their complex "Hold/Release" process, which involves managing stock and ensuring we buy at the right time. The ultimate goal is to boost efficiency and decision quality, especially around critical "buy-windows."

**What was done in this period:**
This past week was a whirlwind of activity, really pushing the project forward on multiple fronts.
*   **Deep Dive into Planning:** We kicked off with a massive documentation effort, really digging into the existing manual planning flows. This involved transcribing complex flowcharts (even recovering arrows from renders, which was a fun challenge!) and clarifying core terminology like "Hold/Release" and some of the Hebrew planning terms. It was crucial to understand the baseline before building on it.
*   **Core Logic Improvements:** A huge win was implementing the "buy-window" as a primary rule. This wasn't just a minor tweak; it significantly boosted our backtest accuracy from 66% to a much more respectable 90%! We also added "NDO enrichment" with things like ABC intervals and neutralizations, which are key metrics that planners rely on.
*   **Planner Integration & UX:** A major focus was making the agent's output genuinely useful and integrated into the planners' existing workflow. This meant creating a consolidated review workbook where agent recommendations appear directly alongside the planner's own data, often in a color-coded tab for clarity. We built an "exceptions-review" feature and worked hard to make the reasons for agent decisions concise and clear. There was also a lot of effort to mine existing planner notes to categorize common reasons and refine our understanding of their needs.
*   **Project Communication:** A significant chunk of time went into creating various visual roadmaps – swimlane diagrams, sequential steps, all translated into Hebrew/RTL for different stakeholders. The goal was to clearly communicate our Q2 MVP and the "what and why" of each step, ensuring everyone was on the same page.
*   **Data Governance & Workflow:** We introduced a PII-safe column-provenance template, allowing planners to document data sources directly within their sheets. This is a big step for data quality, auditability, and building trust in the agent's recommendations.
*   **Refactoring & Cleanup:** Towards the end of the week, I did a big refactor to make the project standalone, ensuring all 28 tests passed. This included vendoring config and making sure imports were clean for easier deployment. Also decommissioned an old transcription service and did a lot of general documentation cleanup and organization.

**What was hard or surprising:**
*   **Excel Integration, My Old Foe:** Man, integrating with existing Excel workflows is always a beast. I initially tried appending agent columns directly to the planner's main sheet, thinking it would be seamless. Nope. It completely broke their existing filters, which was a major headache and caused some frustration. Had to pivot quickly to putting the agent review on its *own* clean tab to preserve their existing workflow. It's a constant reminder that you can't just drop new tech on top of old processes without careful consideration of the human element and their tools.
*   **Domain Complexity:** The sheer depth of the planning domain, with terms like "NDO enrichment," "ABC-interval," and understanding the nuances of "Hold/Release" decisions, was a lot to absorb. Transcribing those manual flowcharts and confirming baselines felt like detective work at times.
*   **Communication Overhead:** While the roadmaps were absolutely crucial, iterating through so many variations (swimlane, sequential, Hebrew, English, with/without emojis, different levels of detail) to get the messaging just right for various audiences was surprisingly time-consuming. It really highlights how much of "dev" work is actually communication and stakeholder management.
*   **Performance Boost:** The "buy-window" rule jumping from 66% to 90% backtest accuracy was a pleasant surprise and a huge morale booster. It felt like we really cracked something important there, and the numbers validated the effort.

**Personal reflection:**
This sprint felt like a real growth period for me. I started feeling a bit overwhelmed by the sheer volume of domain knowledge I needed to absorb and the complexity of the existing manual processes. There were definitely moments of frustration, especially with those Excel filter issues – it felt like I was breaking more than I was fixing for a bit. But pushing through, clarifying requirements with the planners (Sahar and Yulia were invaluable!), and seeing the backtest numbers jump was incredibly rewarding. It reinforced the importance of truly understanding the user's existing workflow, even if it means adapting your technical solution to fit their tools (like Excel) rather than forcing them to adapt to yours. The focus on clear communication, both in the agent's output and in project roadmaps, also felt like a big step forward in my ability to manage stakeholder expectations and articulate value. It's not just about writing code; it's about making that code *land* effectively and be adopted.

**What's next:**
Time to start thinking about the next set of rules and expanding the agent's scope.
